    },
    {
      "ref": "blog-test-6",
      "user_ref": "user-superadmin",
      "kind": "blog",
      "heading": "Debugging Like a Pro",
      "body": "# Debugging Like a Pro\n\nDebugging is an art. Here are my top strategies.\n\n## Essential Techniques\n\n- **Read the error message**: Sounds obvious, but many skip this\n- **Divide and conquer**: Binary search through your code\n- **Rubber duck debugging**: Explain the problem out loud\n\n## Tools I Use\n\n- Print statements (yes, really)\n- Debugger when needed\n- Git bisect for regression bugs\n\nMaster these and you'll save hours!",
      "section_ref": "root",
      "draft": false,
      "featured": false,
      "published_at": "2025-12-16T10:00:00Z"
    },
    {
      "ref": "blog-test-7",
      "user_ref": "user-superadmin",
      "kind": "blog",
      "heading": "The Joy of Simple Solutions",
      "body": "# The Joy of Simple Solutions\n\nToday I refactored 200 lines into 50. It felt amazing.\n\n## What Changed\n\nI realized I was over-engineering. The complex solution wasn't adding value.\n\n## Lessons Learned\n\n- YAGNI: You Aren't Gonna Need It\n- Start simple, add complexity only when needed\n- Simple code is easier to maintain\n\n## The Result\n\nCleaner, faster, and easier to understand. Win-win-win!",
      "section_ref": "root",
      "draft": false,
      "featured": false,
      "published_at": "2025-12-17T10:00:00Z"
    },
